{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623133"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16831"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16831"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.17,0.3,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106290"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9522"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16831"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3949"},{"type":"tags","id":"3953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8763"},{"type":"tags","id":"10342"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39047"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106290"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBrown-Sequard syndrome is a condition resulting from hemisection (injury to one side) of the spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes an expected neurological finding below the level of the lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ipsilateral upper motor neuron weakness","Ipsilateral loss of pain sensation","Ipsilateral loss of temperature sensation","Contralateral loss of vibration sensation","Contralateral loss of proprioception"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn Brown-Sequard syndrome, \u003Cstrong\u003Eipsilateral upper motor neuron weakness\u003C/strong\u003E occurs below the lesion because the corticospinal tract decussates in the medulla oblongata, well above the spinal cord. Therefore, a spinal cord lesion affects the same side as the tract crossing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpsilateral loss of pain sensation\u003C/strong\u003E - Pain sensation is lost on the contralateral side because the spinothalamic tract crosses at the spinal cord level\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpsilateral loss of temperature sensation\u003C/strong\u003E - Temperature sensation, like pain, is lost on the contralateral side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral loss of vibration sensation\u003C/strong\u003E - Vibration sensation is lost on the ipsilateral side as the dorsal column-medial lemniscal pathway has not yet crossed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral loss of proprioception\u003C/strong\u003E - Proprioception, like vibration, is lost on the ipsilateral side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern in Brown-Sequard syndrome is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIpsilateral: weakness, loss of vibration and proprioception\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContralateral: loss of pain and temperature sensation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brown-Sequard syndrome results from hemisection of the spinal cord, causing ipsilateral weakness and proprioception loss with contralateral pain and temperature loss.","The corticospinal tract decussates in the medulla therefore spinal cord lesions cause ipsilateral weakness.","The spinothalamic tract decussates at the spinal cord level causing contralateral pain and temperature loss."],"references":["Moskowitz E, Schroeppel T. Brown-Sequard syndrome. Trauma Surg Acute Care Open. 2018 Feb 20;3(1):e000169. doi: 10.1136/tsaco-2018-000169. PMID: 29766141; PMCID: PMC5887770.","Rodr\u00edguez-Quintero JH, Romero-Velez G, Pereira X, Kim PK. Traumatic Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome: modern reminder of a neurological injury. BMJ Case Rep. 2020 Nov 30;13(11):e236131. doi: 10.1136/bcr-2020-236131. PMID: 33257359; PMCID: PMC7705369.","Shams S, Davidson CL, Arain A. Brown-S\u00e9quard Syndrome. 2024 Feb 27. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30844162."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16831"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88758"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T18:09:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T18:09:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9522"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106290"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"